s://codeberg.org/dnkl/foot/wiki/Performance","score":34,"flags":0,"comment_count":6,"description":"","description_plain":"","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/gl8hqr/when_is_foot_fast_when_is_it_not_2020","submitter_user":"WilhelmVonWeiner","user_is_author":false,"tags":["linux"]},{"short_id":"wu1p2u","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/wu1p2u","created_at":"2024-05-21T16:47:55.000-05:00","title":"How to write \"hookable\" software?","url":"","score":7,"flags":0,"comment_count":8,"description":"\u003cp\u003eDoes anybody have any resources/references/design patterns/guides/blog posts/etc for building software that is designed to be extensible by users?  I have a Kubernetes controller that I’d like to build in some user extension points for, and I’m not really sure the best way to go about this.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eMy rough requirements are\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUsers should be able to write in whatever language they want (or, at the \u003cem\u003every\u003c/em\u003e least, they shouldn’t have to recompile the controller binary)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eI guess I’d \u003cem\u003eprefer\u003c/em\u003e to avoid having a network call/grpc schema/whatever, but maybe that’s the most practical way to do this?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eI’d like a system that can potentially accommodate adding additional extension points in the future\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSecurity (for now) is a non-requirement, the people writing and running this code will already have cluster-admin access to the cluster, and there won’t be a way to accept untrusted code without the person with cluster-admin access approving it.\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"Does anybody have any resources/references/design patterns/guides/blog posts/etc for building software that is designed to be extensible by users?  I have a Kubernetes controller that I'd like to build in some user extension points for, and I'm not really sure the best way to go about this.\r\n\r\nMy rough requirements are\r\n\r\n1. Users should be able to write in whatever language they want (or, at the _very_ least, they shouldn't have to recompile the controller binary)\r\n2. I guess I'd _prefer_ to avoid having a network call/grpc schema/whatever, but maybe that's the most practical way to do this?\r\n3. I'd like a system that can potentially accommodate adding additional extension points in the future\r\n\r\nSecurity (for now) is a non-requirement, the people writing and running this code will already have cluster-admin access to the cluster, and there won't be a way to accept untrusted code without the person with cluster-admin access approving it.","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/wu1p2u/how_write_hookable_software","submitter_user":"drmorr","user_is_author":true,"tags":["ask","distributed","programming"]},{"short_id":"nwvr11","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/nwvr11","created_at":"2024-05-21T16:03:22.000-05:00","title":"A history of a logo with a colon and two slashes","url":"https://daniel.haxx.se/blog/2024/05/21/a-history-of-a-logo-with-a-colon-and-two-slashes/","score":13,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/nwvr11/history_logo_with_colon_two_slashes","submitter_user":"eBPF","user_is_author":false,"tags":["historical"]}]